[
    {
        "content": "<p>Bourke has done a great <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.06375\">study</a> of 2-categories that have a property you might call being 'pseudo-locally finitely presentable': they're finitely accessible, with flexible limits commuting with filtered colimits, and their retract equivalences are accessible. Bourke calls such 2-categories <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">M</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">LP_{\\mathcal M}.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\">M</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> A lot of his argument hinges on showing carefully that the power of an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01445em;\">K</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">M</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">LP_{\\mathcal M}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\">M</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> by the generic arrow <em>with respect to the pseudo-Gray structure</em>, so the 2-category of arrows and <em>pseudo</em> squares in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">K</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal K,</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01445em;\">K</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span></span></span></span> remains in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">M</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">LP_{\\mathcal M}.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1389em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\">M</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 516559439,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1746581053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In particular, this shows that the 2-category of functors and pseudo-squares, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>→</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{PS}=\\mathbf{Ps}(\\to,\\mathsf{Cat})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Ps</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Cat</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is pseudo-locally presentable. But it seems like, in this case, it's actually <em>strict</em> locally presentable. Since it's accessible with products, this just comes down to the existence of equalizers, and I'm pretty sure <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{PS}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span></span> has equalizers: the trick is they're not pointwise, in that in the below situation, you have to define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E_0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0576em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as the intersection of (1) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>g</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{eq}(f_0,g_0)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">eq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1076em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, (2) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>g</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a^*\\mathrm{eq}(f_1,g_1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">eq</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.1076em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, and (3) the equifier of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>φ</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>γ</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\varphi,\\gamma.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> But with that unusual tweak it looks like a perfectly good equalizer ot me. <br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/jda_vRBTdKLUbqmsjS4CzQj3/Screenshot-2025-05-06-at-6.22.28PM.png\">Screenshot 2025-05-06 at 6.22.28 PM.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/jda_vRBTdKLUbqmsjS4CzQj3/Screenshot-2025-05-06-at-6.22.28PM.png\" title=\"Screenshot 2025-05-06 at 6.22.28 PM.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"520x770\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/jda_vRBTdKLUbqmsjS4CzQj3/Screenshot-2025-05-06-at-6.22.28PM.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 516559480,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1746581084
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><strong>Am I missing something</strong>, or am I right that pseudo-squares are locally presentable? If not, is there some general reason why, say, 2-categories of presheaf type in the pseudo sense should be locally presentable, or is this just a brute fact?</p>",
        "id": 516559632,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1746581165
    }
]